        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19019] interaction() should warn when coalescing levels*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19019>\n\n--- Comment #2 from Robert Schlicht (<mailto:robert.schlicht@tu-dresden.de|robert.schlicht@tu-dresden.de>) ---\nIt might not help since `interaction` already calls `as.factor`, which for\ndouble calls `factor`, which in turn calls `as.character`. Here\n`as.character(c(1.0, 1.5))` returns `\"1\" \"1.5\"` and `as.character(c(5.5, 5.0))`\nreturns `\"5.5\" \"5\"`, so when `interaction` concatenates the names with the\nseparator `\".\"`, it gets the identical level `\"1.5.5\"` in both cases. We see\nthis in the last two examples.\n\nI think it is an implementation detail, not a bug, and it is indirectly\ndocumented because the help page for `ave` states that \"Groups are defined by\nthe `interaction` of these variables\" and the help page for `interaction`\npoints out the default `sep = \".\"`. Still, it can be unexpected.\n\nBy the way, `table`, `tapply` and `aggregate` have other strategies for\nconstructing unique levels.",
